article.description:
Alana Beard had 26 points and a
career-high four blocked shots as top-ranked Duke matched the best
start in school history by beating Iowa State 88-59 Sunday night to
win the South Padre Island Shootout.
article.headline: Blue Devils match best start in school history
article.linkText: Beard scores 26, but wants to talk Duke defense after win
article.story:
LOS FRESNOS, Texas (AP) --  Alana Beard had another high-scoring
performance with 26 points, but she was especially pleased with her
defense after top-ranked Duke defeated Iowa State 88-59 Sunday
night to win the South Padre Island Shootout.

	   "That's the main thing I focus on every game, is defense,"
Beard said.

	   She finished with personal-best four blocked shots -- almost half
the team-high nine.

	   "I guess the blocks were just there," she said, refusing to
call the effort "anything special."

	   It was Beard's sixth consecutive game with more than 20 points.

	   The victory was the Blue Devils' 12th straight. Duke also
started 12-0 in the 1987-88 season.

	   "We don't really think about the past too much," coach Gail
Goestenkors said. "We don't focus on the future too much, either.
We just try to take it one game at a time."

	   Lindsey Wilson led Iowa State (4-5) with 20 points. As a team,
Iowa State made 10 of 24 3-pointers with Wilson getting three.

	   "It was a little different defending so many 3-point
shooters," Goestenkors said.

	   Goestenkors said that despite her team shooting only 45.2
percent from the floor, she was more pleased with Sunday's output
than with Friday's 92-52 victory over Detroit.

	   "I felt we had good cuts, good ball movement," she said. "I
was very pleased."

	   Duke took a 7-0 lead in the first two minutes and pulled away.
The lead reached 20-7 on back-to-back baskets by Beard, and the
Blue Devils extended their advantage to 53-28 at halftime.

	   Beard hit 9-of-17 from the field, including 2-of-7 on
3-pointers, and made 6-of-7 free throws. She also had seven
rebounds and three assists.

	   Iowa State coach Bill Fennelly said Beard is a better player
today than when the Cyclones played Duke two years ago.

	   "There's no question she's the top player in the country,"
Fennelly said. "She's stronger, a better perimeter shooter, and
she can score off the rebounds."

	   Iciss Tillis added 14 points for Duke, and Jessica Foley and
Sheana Mosch had 11 each.

	   The three-team tournament was played in a high school gym
because of scheduling conflicts at the South Padre Island
Convention Center. Attendance was 2,000 in a gym that holds 1,500.

	   Fans, ranging from northerners wintering in Texas to local high
school players, didn't mind. Lines reached out to the school
parking lot 90 minutes before the game and the audience was asked
three times to "show a little more love" and make more room.

	   Janet Fisher of Ames, Iowa, said she brought her grandchildren
down just for the game.

	   "They gave up Disney World for the game," she said.

	   The players reveled in the overflowing stands.
	   
"It was awesome to have a packed gym every single night for
three games," Beard said. "It tells you where women's' basketball
is about to go."
